        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-01T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="924" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d924">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.3516/11–146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Durbrow</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-01T16:00:00+03:00">November 1, 1946—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 1—3:41 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4037. Dekanozov<note n="45" xml:id="d924fn45">Vladimir Georgiyevich Dekanozov,
                        Soviet Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> informed by letter dated
                    November first of unsatisfactory telegraphic service between Embassy and Dairen
                    and requested to make necessary arrangements for sending such messages via
                    Vladivostok. (Deptel 1901, October 28.)</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Durbrow</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
